 10  /-!
 11  # Theory of topological modules and continuous linear maps.
 12  
 13  We define classes `topological_semimodule`, `topological_module` and `topological_vector_spaces`,
 14  as extensions of the corresponding algebraic classes where the algebraic operations are continuous.
 15  
 16  We also define continuous linear maps, as linear maps between topological modules which are
 17  continuous. The set of continuous linear maps between the topological `R`-modules `M` and `M₂` is
 18  denoted by `M →L[R] M₂`.
 19  
 20  Continuous linear equivalences are denoted by `M ≃L[R] M₂`.
 21  
 22  ## Implementation notes
 23  
 24  Topological vector spaces are defined as an `abbreviation` for topological modules,
 25  if the base ring is a field. This has as advantage that topological vector spaces are completely
 26  transparent for type class inference, which means that all instances for topological modules
 27  are immediately picked up for vector spaces as well.
 28  A cosmetic disadvantage is that one can not extend topological vector spaces.
 29  The solution is to extend `topological_module` instead.
 30  -/
